HEPATITIS E - CHAD (EASTERN)
****************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
International Journal of Antimicrobial Agents
<http://intl.elsevierhealth.com/journals/ijaa>

Date: Mon 22 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC News Online, Mon 22 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4174074.stm>


An outbreak of hepatitis E has claimed the lives of at least 50 people in
remote villages of eastern Chad. The medical centre in Kerfi is the only
one in a 50-km radius.

In one village alone, scores of people have already died. Aid workers in
the region are trying to help, but there are problems with access. The
village of Kerfi, 80 km from the Sudanese border, is very difficult to get
to. There are few roads and during the rainy season floodwaters create huge
seasonal rivers, called wadis. The only way to reach the village of Kerfi
is to cross the deep, muddy ring of water. Vital medical supplies have to
be floated across the wadi on rafts.

Even though the hepatitis outbreak is slowing down there, more than 50
people in this area near the town of Goz Beida have already lost their
lives. Doctor Camilo Kuan, who has been treating hepatitis patients at the
village clinic, says there still are not enough medical facilities in this
remote corner of Chad. "The medical centre in Kerfi is the only one for 50
kilometres and people can't reach it," Dr Kuan says. "There aren't any
boats, there aren't horses which can cross the wadis -- people have to
swim. So if people are ill they stay at home."

Hepatitis E may not be a headline-grabbing disease like Ebola or HIV/AIDS,
but it can still be deadly. There is no vaccine for the disease, and there
is also no cure.

Souleymane Diabate of UNICEF says that one of the most frustrating aspects
of the disease is how simple it is to prevent - clean drinking water and
good hygiene practices are all that are needed. "It's mainly due to the
fact that most of the localities around Goz Beida don't have drinking
water, the sanitation is really poor and the practice of hygiene also
doesn't exist," she says. "So most of the people are going to the river to
fetch water for consumption. So, most of the population suffer from this
disease."

As [this reporter] learnt from the medical staff here [the village of Goz
Beida], 15 other villages are also suffering from the outbreak of hepatitis
E. The hope now is that supplies get to them before it is too late for even
more people.

[Byline: Stephanie Hancock]

