ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Hepatitis E is an important public health concern in many developing
countries. Hepatitis E is caused by a small single-stranded RNA
calicivirus-like enteric virus now classified as the separate genus
_Hepevivirus_. Hepatitis E virus is transmitted by the fecal-oral route and
is associated with fecal contamination of water supplies. The hepatitis E
mortality rate can reach 25 percent in pregnant women in deprived
communities, but is generally much lower. Although hepatitis E disease only
occurs rarely in countries with good health-care systems, the
seroprevalence rate in healthy individuals can be high.

Hepatitis E disease can be controlled to a large extent by provision of
clean water and adequate sewage treatment facilities. However, there is
increasing evidence that hepatitis E virus is also a zoonotic agent and
that animal reservoirs may exist. Many species of domestic and wild animals
have anti-hepatitis E virus antibodies, and animal hepatitis E viruses
closely related to human hepatitis E viruses have been isolated. Avian
hepatitis E viruses appear to be less closely related to human viruses.
Swine may be an important reservoir of the virus, as pig handlers and
veterinarians appear to be at greater risk of infection, as indicated by
higher antibody levels. Furthermore, cases of acute hepatitis E have
occurred in Japan in association with consumption of raw pig and wild boar
meat.

Lack of an efficient cell culture system has impeded the development of
vaccines and therapeutic agents. - Mod.CP]
